76561198038084472,Not Recommended,244850,32007580,Posted: 27 May,all,fxds,"Space Engineers has the potential to be a fun building game.  Unfortunately in its current state the game is riddled with bugs that frequently kill the fun.  Of course it's still in beta, so perhaps many or even all of the bugs will be fixed before the game is released.  I should also note that all of the bugs my friends and I have encountered were in multiplayer with a dedicated server.  Many of the bugs are supposedly nonexistent in single player but personally I can't imagine this game being fun for very long alone.  Bottom line:  I cannot recommend Space Engineers in its current state.For those who may be curious, bugs my friends and I have encountered include:Horrendous, multi-second freezing/lag (which can and has resulted in ships crashing and being destroyed).  This is not just an unfortunate consequence of unrelated network issues, given that it's usually accompanied by a warning message from the server that the simulation is running slowly, or is clearly tied to specific player action such as another player joining the world.Asteroids completely failing to draw on the sceen, even though the game logic knows they're there (which can and has resulted in ships crashing and being destroyed).Frequent instances of players being unable to move items in ship or base inventory, unable to see items in inventory, or seeing phantom items which were there before but aren't any longer.  Fixing this requires leaving and rejoining the world, but the problem will come back, apparently randomly, after anywhere between five minutes and several hours of play.Large grid ships with airtight compartments randomly going crazy, spinning around rapidly, smashing into anything around them.  There doesn't appear to be any way to recover from this.  Once this happens the ship is literally uncontrollable, meaning player control input (including turning off the thrusters) is completely ignored by the game (using the thruster example again, they stay visibly on despite having been turned off in their control panels)."
