,Recommended,244850,28660033,"Posted: 25 December, 2016",all,Shazam,"Space makes everything cooler, right? No offense to terrestrial enthusiasts, but it's unlikely that a straight-up simulation of everyday engineering would have this kind of pull. By contrast, Space Engineers has a definite hook even in its current Steam Early Access state, which has convinced half a million PC players to pay for pre-release play. While it does feel a whole lot like a celestial take on the sandbox charm of Minecraft, Space Engineers generates its own unique brand of fun, whether you're more interested in constructing things or blasting them to bits.While spawning into a world in Minecraft often reveals mountains and caverns to draw your attention, spinning up a new universe in Space Engineers might drop you into the middle of near-nothingness: just a person in a spacesuit with a jetpack, floating amidst the far-off stars. For most players, it's probably best to start with one of the pre-defined scenarios, which can dump you into a world with a few ships and a platform—something familiar amidst the dead of space, and a home base to start building your own fun around.Whatever your surroundings, Space Engineers' biggest thrill at this point is creating a ship from common parts and zipping around the cosmos. It's amazing how you can simply pull up your inventory, drag a handful of pieces to your toolbar, and build a small working ship in the world in minutes using armor blocks, a cockpit, reactors, thrusters, a gyroscope, and landing gear. Make sure you've got thrusters pointed in all directions and enough juice to power the thing, and you can take off and explore the depths of space in moments. Just like that.And that's just a small ship. It takes a fair bit more time, but you can also build large ships that you can walk around in, as well as outfit them with things like missile turrets, refineries, and medical rooms—plus you can design a space station with many of the same accouterments. While the tools used are simple, your ships and stations can be considerably tweaked in both look and purpose.Granted, that's really the bulk of the game experience right now: building ships and structures, and then toying around with them. But plenty of antagonistic fun is here to be had, too—I had a blast pairing up with an online pal, outfitting our ships with warheads, and then bashing them together and watching the explosive results. Ships and structures tear apart dynamically with each collision or rocket launcher hit, and you can blast holes in space stations large enough to weave tiny ships through. Generating a world full of blazing meteors is a fun twist as well, plus you can hop into others' public or private games for co-op creation or other shenanigans.As of now, Space Engineers includes a couple of ways to experience the action. Creative mode waives resource and inventory restrictions and lets you go crazy with building and design. Meanwhile, Survival mode requires a lot more planning and work, as you'll have to harvest resources from asteroids, craft items, maintain energy levels, and avoid death, lest you want to lose your inventory. Unsurprisingly, it feels like Minecraft's own Survival mode on a basic level, but while it's the more substantial mode of the two here, it comes off like a more time-intensive version of Creative without its own uniquely intriguing aspects—aside from struggling and laboring a lot more. Hopefully it evolves to feel more distinctive than it does now.Being that it's an Early Access game, Space Engineers also doesn't yet have the polish of a full release. I ran into glitches in spots when starting games or connecting to others, and visually the game needs refinement—the engineers just sort of hover around without much in the way of animation, plus the backdrop of the stars looks like a static texture, and it's difficult to get a feel for movement as a result. But those are feasible fixes for a game in this state, and otherwise it's very playable and the core mechanics are solidly in place.Space Engineers does feel a bit thin today, but like the block-based sandbox it seems to take a lot of inspiration from, there's just something about the fundamental building and breaking aspects that holds up during repeat play. Keen Software House has a real opportunity here to expand out from that solid foundation towards a broader and deeper experience in the months to come. For now, you'll make most of your own joy in Space Engineers, whether that's creating things or tearing them to pieces. Usually it's both, and often that's good fun."
