76561198128787850,Not Recommended,244850,34512654,Posted: 26 August,all,Legas,"TL;DR:Absolutely great Spaceship design software and Physic playground.Almost zero gameplay outside designing and building, survival differs nothing from creative except being slower for no reason.If you want a software that allows you great creative freedom to build spaceships, stations, vehicles, contraptions, etc, and then post your creations in the workshop and/or download other people's creations and test them with some rather decent physics simulation, then go right ahead, I recommend the game for you. (if you don't mind the occasional bug)I bought the game over 3 years ago actually wanting a survival experience, having just burned out probably 1000+ hours in survival Minecraft.In Space Engineers however, of my over 700 hours spent probably 90%+ of it was on creative. I'm now going to expand on why survival experience falls short of the expectation:1) Everywhere you may be you'll have access to all ores and resources in plentiful quantities within 1km radius, also you may travel a hundred kilometers and everything will look exactly the same, there is no differeces anywhere, no 'biomes', no different resources, enemies or whatever, be it in space or planets. This makes exploration void, you have absolutely no reason to travel anywhere from the starting point.2) One single block process absolutely all ores in the game, and another build all components, there is zero depth to crafting and all opportunities for tech trees are removed.3) The starting drill can mine all ores in the game, again losing opportunity for actual progress in the form of better tools.4) As soon as you spawn you have access to every single block in the game and also the resources to build them without any sort of progress whatsoever. This completely removes the 'sense of progress' of the player, you may be several hours within gameplay or mere minutes, everything is the same.5) Nearly zero survival pressure, once you mine some uranium so you don't run out of energy, you'll realistically never face death risk due to survival elements ever again.6) No environmental hazards, with the exception of meteor showers, which are horribly unbalanced and just keep bothering you ad nauseum until you decide to turn them OFF.7) Almost all gameplay features in the game are very unbalanced, be it block weight/efficiency, ore rarity, refining times, weapons, energy sources (you have solar panels and batteries, but why bother when you could mine uranium for 10 minutes and have enough energy for a lifetime without any drawbacks?)8) Enemy AI is garbage and combat is overall extremely unbalanced, unrewarding and easily (and best) avoided, limiting one of the main drives to build and grow, also removing what could easily be the 'end-game content'9) Lack of any meaningful direction: after you set up your base/ship and solve the energy issue, then there is nothing else to do, you've finished the game within 1-2 hours of gameplay. You could build a warship, more refineries or a satellite or a car, but why? Nothing in the game compels you to do so, and anything you do or build beyond the basic will be completely empty of meaning and unrewarded. There are no challenges to conquer, no enemies to defeat, no unknown to discover... you just feel alone in a vast and empty universe wondering why you wasted so much time for what seems to be no reason at all.(I know all games are meaningless and waste of time in the end, but most games make a good job of keeping the player from noticing that, Space Engineers on the other hand actually go out of it's way in every opportunity to shove in the player's face the futility of his works)10) Multiplayer interactions could replace or fix several of these problems, but heavy lag, poor performance, bugs, unbalanced mechanics, crashes, desynch, griefing and overall bad game design decisions soon render Multiplayer unbearable...Conclusion:Stay away if you want any meaningful survival experience. If you, like me, just had some amazing survival experience, such as Minecraft, full of wonder, unknown, exploration, danger and combat, you won't find any of this here.The Devs might fix these problems with time, but, frankly, I don't really see it happening in the next 10 years in the current development pace, specially when the Devs seem to have zero direction to where the game is going and trying to make the game do everything (Dogs? Player Skins? Scenario Editor?) but in reality failing even in the most basic gameplay features."
