76561198064476908,Recommended,244850,28222767,"Posted: 6 December, 2016",all,Captain Colgate,"This is the game that no man's sky was supposed to be.Kind of.doing cons first, as a tl;dr why you might not want this amazing piece of game.CONS, in order from most to least severe:-Development has been sloooow.The development branch of SE updates weekly, with the stable branch updating monthly, I believe. It's hard to expect revolutionary gameplay changes on a regular basis, but even still, many of the updates are fairly small and mostly contain changes for the sake of mod support or minor bugfixes. The game is still worth playing, but It may be a while before it's finished.-Planets are a bit boring.Space is also boring because it's so empty, but space is just like that. But planets still feel barren and somewhat samey, even with different seeds for random generation. With some luck, more detail will be added to the procedural generation system to allow for things like caves and more detailed biomes- similar to how minecraft works. At the moment, a ""biome"" in SE basically just means a slight difference in the texture on the ground and how bumpy the terrain is. There are a few hostile enemies that spawn as well, but they feel very unfinished and don't add a lot to the gameplay. Generally they just spawn out of nowhere and make a beeline for you or things that you've built, then stand still attacking it until they die or their target dies.It would also be cool to have some weather effects. Just saying.-Fairly demanding game to run.I suspect that a decent gaming computer will run it well (my rig isn't exactly a 'beast' but it runs 60-80 fps at moderate settings) but you're not going to get much out of a generic 150$ laptop from best buy. It's possible that optimization will improve in the future, but at the time of this writing the game definitely needs a good PC to run.-Bugs do crop up from time to time, and there are a handful of quality-of-life issues that i'll rattle off now;--Remote camera overlays are annoying and make it nearly impossible to see when piloting a remote ship. Fortunately, this can be easily fixed with mods.--There are a few features missing that would be nice have in the game, but don't seem to be currently supported- such as locking an axis of rotation on a gyroscope to prevent ships from rotating in a certain direction, or getting GPS coordinates from antennas or beacons. (I don't know if other people have suggested these, but they're things I'd like to see)--Ore detectors and other coordinates seem to be based on the position of the player rather than the camera or the detector itself. This isn't a major issue, but it does mean that if you're trying to pilot a remote-controlled mining ship towards an ore deposit, it may be difficult to tell exactly where it is.--conveyor systems seem a little bit wonky at the moment, i've had instances where I've spent hours gathering hydrogen fuel only to have my hydrogen tanks suddenly vent it all for no apparent reason. Oxygen generators also don't ""share"" resources like other production items do. If you put a chunk of ice through a connector, it will all go to the nearest oxygen generator rather than splitting evenly between several, the same way reactors will evenly split up uranium ingots.--Rotors are a pain to use if you want to have limits on their rotation. you have no real reference for angles other than their current degree of rotation, which means setting the upper and lower limits for rotating is basically done through trial and error. (there's probably a better way to do it, but I'm stupid)So Pros, then. Now in paragraph form, because these were harder to put in a list format.One thing that I really enjoy about this game is the amount of dynamic problem-solving and experimentation involved in building a ship, especially in survival mode. There are a few basic mechanics to ship-building that you can pick up from the tutorial, but the tutorial only shows you how to build one kind of ship. Space is a pretty demanding place to live, and just one kind of spaceship isn't really going to cut it. Eventually, you're going to have to get creative.This means quite a lot of trial and error and a lot of experimenting. Every planet has a slightly different environment, and every survival run is going to have slightly different factors involved (depending on how you set it up). You might end up on a planet without breathable air, creating a need for remote-controlled ships or ships with built-in oxygen generators. Or maybe you're trying to get from one planet to another, meaning you'll need to build a ship with powerful enough engines to get you out into space and then land again. Or maybe you're not on a planet at all, and have to build a ship that can quickly move between asteroids to gather resources.The game has no set list of goals to achieve. Similar to minecraft, you must decide your own endgame, and then take on whatever challenges that goal might involve. But unlike minecraft, in which you ultimately can't create much more than simple machines, decorative buildings, and big holes in the ground, SE lets you really interact with your creations. You can build a model of a huge space shuttle in MC, sure- but only Space Engineers lets you experience flying it.And when you do finally build that shuttle capable of escaping your planet's gravity, there's no feeling more satisfying than looking out the window at the continent you had to turn inside out for resources, and the graveyard of broken or obsolete mining ships that weren't worth fixing or grinding down for scrap metal.Then you have an embarassing crash landing on another planet and realize that the planet you were on before was actually a much nicer place to live."
