76561197967501808,Not Recommended,244850,29550038,Posted: 28 January,all,Thrashaero,"There is a lot of fun to be had in this game if you like building things in space. OR IF YOU JUST ENJOY GOING INSANE. It is a patience test the likes I have never seen. I like hardcore/challenging games but this goes into absurd territory too often. Once the initial cool factor of space building wears off, it is just a futility/space madness simulator, which it excels at in every way imagineable. Cool graphics and neat functions are very addictive at first, time will fly incredibly fast. Spending many hours throughout the night just to get that next thing built, it will only take a few minutes, you keep putting off bed. Then out of nowhere some inexplicable, random explosion sends all of your stuff that took time to mine, refine, assemble, transport, weld, and configure to be scattered about and deleted as the server detects you're not within some tiny range of the objects. Boy that was fun, it's now 5am all for nothing. Not once, but a couple dozen times this has basically been the case over the years of coming and going every few months. Like a fool, I keep trying to give it a chance. For just maybe one more time I'll get lucky or I just have to put that one extra ounce of effort in and things will be just dandy.Yeah, I know what you're saying. It's all my fault, x catastrophe happened for a perfectly explainable reason. blah freakin blah. But after almost 900 hours and careful investigation of causes I know the difference between what is my fault and what is because of the game. I don't use pistons, rotors, landing gears, nor any mods beyond experimentation and I'm being as careful as possible, one thing at a time, graphics on lowest, on an empty server, <50 ping, good server settings, and i have 16gb ram, 8core 4ghz cpu... but nope, still not good enough?Don't build too much, don't use this, don't do that, must do this before that then this then that...then that's it. Actual large ship combat is a pipe dream, starting a decent foundation to commence such is loaded with constant setbacks. I don't mind figuring out a long list of getting things done, or dealing with a bit of stuttering, and of course my own mistakes and bad planning, but it is extremely tedious and limiting to have to trial and error everything to avoid nonsense issues and there to be little to do otherwise, trying to avoid whatever random BS will happen next.  It is walking on thin ice, all the time.I know what you're saying. It's space, it's dangerous, it's this it's that. Or it's a complex game, it is very hard to program blah blah. Yes, I know. Things will work just fine just enough to get your hopes up that you can move on to the next operation only to bring you down again, having nothing to do with the dangers of space or your actions, just purely the game being stupid and requiring a million band-aids to hobble things along. Usually thanks to processing a stupid amount of data that could be more efficiently handled as well as crappy networking. But that's understandable when things go bad, when there's a lot going on. I'm talking about when you're by yourself and performance is grand, you still get SNAFU's that will make you pull your hair out and cuss furiously. Unless that sort of thing gives you the warm fuzzies.It is loaded with a million features and complex layering of which can seem amazing at first that it works at all, until you realize there's simply too much, making the mp performance terrible and otherwise glitchy as all hell.  The most fun you'll have is exploring workshop entries and messing around in single player in my opinion, but that gets old quick as there is no game otherwise to work towards. The AI is non-existent. Just some cheesy simple spiders and wolves and aimbot ships. No AI characters or factions. Just scripted ships with red signals. It's more of a base/ship making sandbox sort of interactive editor with no real depth of goals to fulfill beyond the chores of mining, fixing stuff/rebuilding and making workarounds because of all the ridiculous conflicts.This is all besides the fact that there is no true physics in the game except locally floating components/ores and ship controls. Planets do not rotate, the sun is geocentric (revolves around everything in the skybox), there are no orbits, etc. No basic temperature of any kind except thruster damage. Things that are essential considerations to space travel. But of course those are the most minor of complaints.Multiplayer: Unless you're lucky to have a few friends on a good LAN, multiplayer is a complete sh!tshow unless you're a masochist. Stuff which took forever to build since most servers want super realism rates as well as having to find some safe space to not get looted immediately. That is IF you don't have the beacon/antenna bug that broadcasts to everyone on the server your location no matter the distance or settings, the items of which are required to keep ships on most servers ironically enough, the thing that allows you to be ignored by cleanup scripts is the bait that attracts the looters. Not to mention all of the horrific lag spikes and sim speed issues, where there is yet to be any decent multithreading to be seen. Then you can't rejoin the server since it's not updated to the latest version or it went off line for a while and you usually lose all your stuff. I simply don't play much anymore, it's always infuriating, a waste of time.Then add  the community is plagued with a lot of complete d!ckheads. I can't count how many times I've been crapped on just for asking a basic question or voicing a normal concern that would come from anybody who doesn't base their entire life around the game. I can understand tough love for mindless curiosities but if you're not in the cult of understanding all of the esoteric ways in which this game screws with you, then the asperger-ridden, spoiled d0uchebag geeks and their equally braindead sycophants drop in and cut you off at the pass eager to start sh!t and troll you away, taking whatever issue you're having personally because their life has nothing else invested, apparently. How they tolerate each other is beyond me. *cough* FOUNTAINCORE *cough*  Most of the nice people I've met are those that play this crap as rarely as I do.We keep getting excuses that it's early access blah blah blah but how long is this going to drag on for? How many years has it been now? We're going on 4 years and it's been in open development how long and where are the significant improvements? There's simply too many hands in too many cookie jars with this clusterfuc|< for it to be a game worth wasting time on any time soon. For all the good press the game has received for their ability to keep pushing updates consistently and have as many sales as they have and the awards given...how do they still not have the programming/director talent required to get this out of dev hell? I know they are an indie dev unit and programming isn't easy but at what point do you graduate the amateur sphere and move to become/hire professionals when you're raking in the money?Right now the game is only for uber geek fanboys with supercomputers who enjoy never ending bugs and zero criticism. Pin the blue ribbon upon their chests for masochist excellence.If you want a better, real in depth review check this one out:http://steamcommunity.com/id/leewells2000/recommended/244850/Also, I see a lot of reviews recommending Empyrion. It looks better in general. Time to get in the escape pod and jump ship, but i'm not holding my breath."
