,Not Recommended,244850,35202019,Posted: 25 September,all,White Rhino PSO,"I bought Space Engineers very soon after the developers added a Survival Mode. Back then, the game was very stable; I could spend hours working to survive while slowly taking apart my wrecked starting ship and rebuilding it into something of my own design. When they added an endless, procedurally generated universe complete with abandoned ships and stations to find, I couldn't have been happier. I lost countless hours to Space Engineers and never looked back.And then the game's community rallied for the developers to add planets. The idea of adding planets to the game was never part of the original plan, and it took months to force them to exist and work in an engine that wasn't designed for it. I don't know if this was really the tipping point, but it certainly feels like it on looking back.The game, as it stands, is nearly unplayable due to the number of bugs that have been introduced in ever growing numbers. There's no reason to bother with Survival Mode any longer, because the game will happily destroy whatever you've spent hours building for no known reason. Features like pistons and rotors will be perfectly stable one day, and then rip your ship apart from the inside the next time you load your save. Wheels and rotors need you to spend hours tweaking their settings in-game, and even after that they still don't work correctly.Keen Software House decided the best way to continue work on their product was to.. nickel and dime the playerbase. Where in games like Factorio, playing older versions are simply an option in a drop-down menu in the ""betas"" tab for the game. In Space Engineers, they expect you to pay $9.99 for the ""deluxe edition,"" which lets you play the original creative-only game as it was when it first hit Steam. And now, as of writing this review, they've decided to start selling ""engineer skins"" in pieces, with each of the four pieces costing players anywhere from $1.49 to $2.49.I've lost all hope for this game. Endless Early Access shenanigans where every Thursday the update would claim to fix bugs and issues only for the game forums and subreddit to say that no, the bugs are still there, and have somehow gotten even worse. But Keen would rather try and squeeze more money out of their playerbase than actually knuckle-down and fix their game so that people can play what they bought into.I have over 300 hours of play time for this game, most of which were spent during the early days after Survival Mode was added, some of the most fun I've had in any survival-crafting game. With the way the game has slowly twisted, broken, and still had the gall to reach for my wallet, I'm honestly regretting having ever given Space Engineers my time or money."
