,Recommended,244850,9692316,"Posted: 31 March, 2014",all,SoUlFaThEr,"In its Alpha stages the game is already cool for a few hours, but can get boring rather fast because there is not much to do yet in my opinion. It requires some patience due to its Early Access business model. It has a great deal of potential at being a nemesis to Minecraft for space exploration with better graphics, but will seemingly require a great deal of work to reach that status. You have multiple scenarios at your disposal, but in each, it is basically the same at the moment; you need to find Uranium as fast as you can while at the same time save your given energy in the games various styles of survival beginnings.There is a multiplayer mode that is not yet in the condition it should be but it is getting there slowly but surely. Things take time, of course. Dedicated servers seem to be a step for the developers in the near future so players can build huge things with their friends...and destroy them.A decently high computer is required. Mine is sort of lower mid range at the moment and there are some graphical bugs due to that and presently multiplayer seems to me impossible to play. Like I said though, if you are a player who enjoys going out and gathering resource to build a huge space station or some ships to your exact liking with not-so-many-yet building parts yet then this is a game for you. I can't wait until it has AI to fight off however, and a faster way of moving the high amount of resources you mine from asteroids into processing and storage. It has weapons and blocks designed for item transport but it isn't finished yet due to, again, the Early Access model. It's still an Alpha build and for that, is damn good already.In the end, a game with a great deal of potential. If you enjoy idea of ""survival in space"" then this is for you for sure."
,Recommended,244850,11375151,"Posted: 23 July, 2014",all,CyberFerret,"Space Engineers is not minecraft in space. Ok so now that we have that out of they way, Space Engineers is a great game if you want to create ships with guns and blow stuff up. In its current state the multiplayer is playable but sometimes abit buggy, but that is to be expected from an alpha state. The game offers two modes, Creative and Survival. In creative mode you can build what ever you want with no need to collect resources, this is good if you just want to build some wonderfull ships. The Survival mode is just what its name suggests, unlike Creative mode you have to actually mine resources to build parts in this mode. In my personal opinion Survival mode is best played with friends as playing it alone can become boring very fast, but with friends it is very enjoyable and fun. The game is updated every Thursday which is nice as it is something to look forward to.In final review I would give this game in its current state a 8.9/10, it would have been a 10 if not for some multiplayer problems, but as I said the game is updated regually so prehaps these issues will be fixed soon.I hope this review was helpfull."
76561198039977423,Recommended,244850,12440550,"Posted: 10 October, 2014",all,LethalOwl,"Space Engineers is, as I write this, in version Alpha 01.051. I would like to put emphasis on the fact that it is Alpha early access. This is not a finished product, but I shall review it as it is right now. Edits may come.Space Engineers is, in short, an amazing space-based sandbox with physics. As Marek Rosa himself compared it with; It's kind of like Lego Technic. But if you want a comparison with other games, I'd say along the lines of Minecraft and, a game that I haven't played, Kerbal Space Program. You will find a lot of reviewers saying the same thing, because there's not much of a better comparison to make.The game offers 2 modes to be played; Creative and Survival. The creative mode allows you to build the spaceship / spacestation of your dreams. Or perhaps recreate a ship from one of your favorite games, series or movies that you've seen / played before. Meanwhile the survival mode puts you in the role of a space engineer that, at the current state of the game, is required to collect materials through mining in asteroids and from there on progress to build a station, more ships to make all this go swifter - and then possibly go pirating on passing cargo ships. Survival doesn't have much to offer as of yet.A way to make survival, in a way, more ""fun"" is through creating scenarios. Basically you can go into creative and create yourself a prepared world for a survival adventure later on! Everything from building bases and ships and hazards that the survival players will have to deal with, or even small 'mini-games'. This is one of the things that can make survival slightly more amusing.As most would agree right now; Survival is not fun alone for the most part and I'd say you'd enjoy this mode best alongside 1 or several other players. Creative mode, in my opinion, is better off done alone - Unless your creativity is severely lacking and wouldn't mind a helping hand in your creative builds.This game is worth the investment that it costs for what it offers and what it will offer in the future. With a VERY DEDICATED AND ACTIVE development team, this game shows more promise than most Early Access games do and should truly be the standard to expect of indie developers. Enthusiastic devs with great interest in what they're making. And with a lot of listening to the community. A lot of the additions to this game so far is because the PLAYERS ASKED. With the addition of modding to the game, and with that a very active modding community with more tools to make this a truly enjoyable experience, the ideas are quite endless.As a alpha-stage game, there are bugs and there will be more bugs - But there will also be bug-fixes. I'd like to say that if you're here for a survival-based experience with an end-goal and progression-styled gameplay with AI / mobs included to fend off to make your survival experience more epic... This isn't in the game yet. But as we progress, it is likely we will see these things very soon. If not through the developers, the modding community will surely get it done. But I'm fairly certain that the developers will get some sort of AI in to make the survival mode worthwhile.I'd say save your coins if you're not at all interested in this kind of game, but otherwise - Even if you're not going to play it much 'yet' - it is worth investing the cheap price for it to help the development of something that will truly be an amazing game in the end (It already is, really).The opportunities are endless. What will you be building? Join us in the quest to shape the one of the most amazing games ever made by an indie development team!- LethalOwl"
,Recommended,244850,12191830,"Posted: 22 September, 2014",all,RPINerd,"Space Engineers is a phenomenal example of how the Early Access program can be a real positive addition to the Steam ecosystem. The developers seem to be on top of this project and show a lot of passion for the game and even more for the players they are building this game for.I suppose it's inevitable that this game be called Minecraft in space, and while it's hard to argue that this is not an appropriate description I feel that it doesn't do this title justice. Space Engineers isn't just a rubbish Minecraft knockoff with a space skin on it; from the beginning this game was developed to stand on it's own as a sandbox, spacemining, crafting and combat simulator.The game, in it's current state, is fully functional; I cannot say the optimization is the best as of the writing of this early impressions but updates are frequent and content is still pouring in. I think for most people you're just as well off to wait until at least beta because I can see the content becoming stale for those who go in with just a mild interest in the idea of the game, however if you're a fan of sandbox gameplay and really love space, you won't regret picking up Space Engineers!"
