,Recommended,244850,24865473,"Posted: 12 August, 2016",all,RockstarCRO,"This game is insanely big in it's concept. Almost anything you can think of is right here in this game regarding space. Space ships? Check. Travel between planets or around planets? Check. Work in space? Check. Build space stations, ships (from attack ships to resource ships)? Check. An intricate power supply system or conveyor belts with control panels? Check. Loads of tools to work and craft with? Check. This game can be lotus for the space fans.Space Engineersgameplayis pretty decent at the moment. The movement and frame rate is smooth but some major lag can appear in certain servers if you're playing online. All essential movements are here from sprinting, jumping and crouching. Additional features include the ability to turn off inertial dampeners, a flashlight and activate a jet pack which allows the player to move freely in all three axis. The jet pack doesn't use any fuel at the moment unless you're playing in a certain mode. Either way, I like having the ability to move around and craft without worrying if I can get to the top of the structure. The player may also zoom in the camera as they please and may even play in first person mode. Smaller ships are piloted in first person mode while larger ships are only seen from 3rd person (as you will move about in larger ships). Ships are also equipped with a flash-light ability by pressing L.Building is relatively simple in game but can take a bit of time to properly master and get what you want. The basic building unit in Space Engineers is blocks. Blocks can be cosmetically small, large, rounded and edged. The player doesn't simply build blocks and then have a ship. Power supplies (that come in blocks), doors, antennas, cockpit, connectors, control panels, conveyors, windows, seats and even guns can be added. The player will need to build a power supply for any vehicle or air unit they plan to build. Engineers can also build ground units and stations using any combination of block they please. Power is transferred through blocks once they are touching so there isn't a need to become an electrician and run wire. Some useful key shortcuts are ctrl+p (to pick a color), shift+p (to set a color to selected block), ctrl+mouse1 (hold) to place multiple blocks in a straight line and ctrl+shift+mouse1(hold) to place multiple blocks on a plane.There are currently two game modes in Space Engineers : survival and creative. Survival mode requires players to collect components/materials to construct objects. Welding also takes a lot more time in this mode. If a player dies, there is a good chance (unless the material is stored), that the material on the player will be lost. To make it even more difficult, every space suit in this mode is given a certain amount of life support. The player will need to recharge or face the ultimate consequence of not breathing oxygen. Creative mode allows the player to respawn as many times as they want without losing any of their material. Moreover, this mode allows players to build as much as they want for no cost. These blocks are also created instantly and do not need to be welded or pre-made. In either mode, random enemies can attack the player. Players do not need to worry about energy/oxygen/hydrogen levels in this mode.When I mean this game is big, it's quite big. It will take some time to learn and definitely take some time to create something significant. Players can be placed in different settings such as earthly, martian, alien, moon or even asteroids to begin building their legacy. There are scenarios to choose from in which will put the player in all sorts of scenarios. Some scenarios will come with already made stations while in others you may start with extremely minimal parts. Players will want to equip their starships (or themselves) with some fire power before exploring the wilderness. Some ship weapons include gatling guns and turrets, rocket launchers, missile turrets and warheads. Hand-held weapons are slightly limited at the moment but include an automatic rifle, a grinder and a hand drill.Graphicsare pretty good at the moment but sometimes have an occasional hiccup. It's nothing game-breaking or anything but is noticeable.Overall, it's a pretty good game and the fact it's still early access and being updated is fantastic. It's a BIG game though and would recommend patience while playing. I'm very impatient myself and like simply jumping in the game and playing. This is possible but you'll catch yourself asking ""how do I do..."" a few times while looking up information on the internet. There is a good tutorial that will help the player discover how to properly master the game. There is still a lot that can be added to this game to make it better (like a sumo mode)!!! Some may find it's appeal fun for the first 5-10 hours then look the other way while others may indulge in such a space adventure. It's all up to the creativity of the player to determine their entertainment.EARLY ACCESS RATING : 7/10ScreenShots : (to come)"
