76561198015383586,Recommended,244850,11190026,"Posted: 11 July, 2014",all,Beezil,"Space Engineers: Early Access Alpha Review - This review is for Alpha build 1.038.013Is This Game for Me?First thing you might ask is, is this game worth getting? That depends on a few things. First and foremost is do you like building games? If you like building games like Minecraft or Terraria and you have a PC that can handle it, then without reservation I can say you’d be crazy NOT to get it.What Kind of Game is It?What is Space Engineers exactly? If I could describe it one sentence I’d say it’s a Newtonian physics based space simulation/voxel-based building/survival game. I’m nearing 400 hours into the game and I’m showing no signs of losing interest any time soon. Those who know me, know there are only two other games I’ve put more than a 100 hours into; Mass Effect 3 and Skyrim. That’s pretty rarified company for an indie developed, $20 game. In Space Engineers you scavenge or mine for resources that you then make into building components with which you use to build stuff. At the same time you have to survive the harsh environment of space.It’s an Alpha!Yes it is an alpha game which nine times out of ten means it’s a buggy mess (more or less) with few features implemented. Not so with Space Engineers. It’s a remarkably stable for an early access game and though the full list of features are far from having been implemented, it already has a very robust feature list that has kept me busy for nearly 400 hours and counting. This doesn’t mean you won’t encounter bugs. You will, but they are very seldom game breaking and the devs have displayed a pattern of working hard to address bugs on a regular basis.Patchmas!!!!What’s Patchmas you ask? It’s something I’ve never seen a dev do. Every Thursday Keen Software House releases an update patch for the game which includes new items, new features  and bug fixes. Unlike other early access games you don’t have to wait for a month or two to get new features and see bugs fixed. With Space Engineers you’ll see something new every single week. That’s right. You heard me correctly. Every week you get new toys to play with in the game. And in between those patches, there are hotfixes that address bugs. So even though the game is far from finished, you’ll see new features added to the game EVERY WEEK. In fact, Keen has been quoted as saying they never want to stop developing the game, even after final release.Game ModesThere are three game modes. First is creative mode which allows you to build things without having to gather resources or worry about survival issues. Everything you build comes into being instantly instead of having to weld it together. You can’t die in creative mode.Second is survival mode which is either solo or you can have your friends come in and help you out. In this mode you must gather resources, make sure don’t die, and deal with hazards. Hazards are probably the most underdeveloped portion of the game presently but that’s definitely a feature in the game that promises to be very interesting once it’s progressed far enough in development.The third mode is PvP with dedicated servers. I have very little experience with this mode as I don’t generally go for that kind of gameplay but from what I’ve seen on the Keen forums, which I monitor regularly, the PvP mode is the mode that is more prone to bugs and is not as far along in development as other modes in the game. Even given that, there’s still a LOT of people regularly playing in this mode. It’s something that very likely will become more awesome as the game progresses, and once it does progress far enough I might even give it a go even though I don’t usually go for PvP.In short, Space Engineers is a game that anyone who likes to build stuff would be crazy not to give a go. If you are one of those people, then pony up $20 and give it a go. I’m betting you won’t be sorry.Edit: I forgot to add that the game already had a dedicated modding community. The AAA SE mod pack is especially awesome. If you get the game, be sure to check it out on the Official Keen Software House forums. You won't be sorry you did."
