,Recommended,244850,9978676,"Posted: 30 April, 2014",all,shogeki,"Space is a cold, unforgiving place.  This is the world that waits for you in Space Engineers, a voxel-based sandbox game similar to Minecraft but with enough twists to mark its own territory in the genre.In Space Engineers, you must temper the harsh realities of space with a limited set of tools:  A space suit that lasts only a few minutes before requiring a recharge, a set of construction tools (Welder, Grinder, and Drill), and perhaps a space station or ship to keep you alive with scant Uranium fuel.  To last more than a couple of hours, you must find more fuel, via mining ore, which must be put through a refinery before it can be used.  Without Uranium, you can't make more, so making a mistake will cost you your life - and if your ship runs out of fuel - may cost you your progress.  Beyond basic survival, the stars are the limit.  You have your choice of producing the parts for and constructing small ships, large ships, or space stations.  The latter two cost an incredible amount of resources but are strangely satisfying to slave away welding together 2.5 metre blocks of steel for hours on end.  Time invested mining can be minimized with construction of a mining ship and a base to properly refine your ore.Though scarcely an Alpha version, Space Engineers is an incredibly fun and rewarding experience, but as such you must be willing to put up with occasional glitches and clunky multiplayer."
,Recommended,244850,11176918,"Posted: 10 July, 2014",all,Preowned,"It is good fun, good sandbox game, and survial mode is fun.Active dev means I can wait to see how this game gets better."
,Recommended,244850,7543332,"Posted: 1 November, 2013",all,TwistedLogic,"Every single time I put this game down thinking I'm done for a bit, I think of another interesting thing I can build and test out and have to load the game back up and start testing it. A new ram, different shape ships, a new mechanism that could work just so or something really daft like a small ship made almost entirely out of small warheads. At the moment, multiplayer is just single player with more people, but that works. Things are made infinitely more fun with the inclusion of other people and Space Engineers is no different. For those of you waiting to get SE when multiplayer was added, now is your chance.-:Update:-New survival mode is awesome. Crafting can be a bit daunting at first, but once you get the hang of it, it all comes together and makes even the simplest construction feel fantastic! The lack of objectives in single player survival might put some off, but the multiplayer survival is going to be great co-op or versus fun :D-:Update number 2:-Ok, having limited things and trying to create complicated things by using those really limited simple things was really good fun right? Space Engineers is still good, don't get me wrong, but sandbox games always seem to do this; they take those really complex ideas people have... and simplify them. They simplify them, cram them into an in-game, single, EASY item... and make it boring. Previously, if you wanted a door, you built one. You set up rotors, maybe even pistons in the later iterations, connector blocks, convoluted processes to do the simplest things. Now, you place a door block. Job Done. No challenge, no creativity. Slap a block down, wham! instant door.Personally, this turns things dull for me, but if you like this kind of thing, definitely check out SE as it has only been made better in that respects. This has been a fantastic game from the beginning."
