76561198048249227,Recommended,244850,19175574,"Posted: 20 November, 2015",all,fortuiteer,"My recommendation: DON'T BUY THE GAME IF YOU CAN'T HANDLE THE DISAPPOINTMENT THAT MIGHT COME WITH AN EARLY ACCESS TITLE, REGARDING BUGS AND PERFORMANCE ISSUESMy thoughts on the game:Impressive achievement!I see a lot of negative comments, mostly related to the game performing worse under the strain of rendering the new feature of enormously gigantic planets with flora and fauna. I guess it's fair that these people are giving a warning to potential buyers. But the derogatory and hateful undertones are entirely out of place.So far I have seen only two other game engines that render a near limitless visibility distance while providing huge planets, which can even be terra-formed (meaning, you can morph the terrain). The other titles are ""Stellar Overload"" (formerly known as ""Planets3"") and ""Seed of Andromeda"" (not yet a released game, but rather a pre-pre-alpha version. I did get to actually play it myself, though). ""No Man's Sky"" might be another such game, but I don't know the extent of its terra-forming/building features. They might be relatively simple in comparison.It cannot be stressed enough how difficult it is to code a stable engine for huge sandbox worlds, when simulated physics, creature AI and complex crafting/building are involved. Add to that multiplayer, pretty graphics and an excessive visibility range = unavoidable trouble on the bug-front.With that in mind, Keen Software House have created a fairly impressive engine, so far. There are bugs and performance isn't flawless on my mediocre system (a ~500$ PC), but the framerate is smooth (40+ fps) at *most* times (there are some freezes every couple minutes), with the visual settings close to max (I don't use anti-aliasing and anisotropic filtering, but they shouldn't affect performance a lot). In single-player mode I didn't encounter noteworthy bugs, but I have no doubt they'll show up. Why? Because that's a normal in all programs that go beyond the previously established borders of their specific genres.Movement between space and planets happens without any transition. Unfortunately that also means there is no visible entry of a planet's atmosphere, but the smooth, transitionless movement, while watching the planet's surface closing in, is the more important feature.The player is free to leave the pilot's seat at any time and walk around inside the ship. The size of a planet is a little overwhelming when you leave the ship and realize how much slower you move on foot, but it's also quite thrilling.With just 60 minutes of playtime, I didn't even get a short glimpse at the crafting/building feature, but I already know it's very complex and was the game's primary selling feature, before the ""planets"" update.The game isn't finished yet and no one could guarantee that it'll ever be released without bugs (see ""Frontiers"" developer Lars Simkins's ""November Update"" of 2015 on Youtube, for a relatively in-depths description on that topic).In that respect, whoever buys the game should have a true ""explorer"" spirit. In past centuries exploration meant taking serious risks to your health and even life, without any retries on failure.Space Engineers will allow you to explore its game world and bugs. And you might find yourself failing on the latter. But at least you get retries."
