76561198013804828,Not Recommended,244850,24007212,"Posted: 1 July, 2016",all,Paddywacko,"See below for my original post, as it still has merit in my opinion, however I've spent more time trying to see what this game has to offer. If you're new to it and looking to try the survival mode as I was, turn the environmental hazards off, and don't play on a planet world. They are relentless and make the game virtually unplayable for a new player.Why? Planets have robot dogs that apparently eat metal and space engineers, and prefer to spawn in packs of 3-6 every 1-4 minutes. This results in dying several times per hour, and a naturally occuring ""game reset"" as they consume both your body and the three blocks you've managed to build since the last time you died.Also, the environmental hazards are meteor storms that spawn centered on your head once every five minutes. They might not kill you, but they wreck any bases they touch. For example, I was robodog free on an asteroid base with a pre generated reactor and some crafting machinery. I thought the meteor storms were cool until one spawned on my head instead of somewhere else in ""infinite"" space and hit nothing. Except the reactor, which it obliterated. I had been playing for maybe 15 minutes at this point, so I had some components. I thought I would just build another one, but discovered I was still short some required components. I thought ""No problem, I'll just craft them really fast."" Pause.I need components to build a reactor.I need an assembler to build components.I need a reactor to power an assembler.Ergo, I floated off into space and died after about an hour of scrambling to find Step 1 that every sandbox survival game should have. Turns out Step 1 in Space Engineers is ""Start new game"" where they hand you a reactor, a refinery, and an assembler because the game is unplayable without any one of those things.Where this game currently shines is in the building. Once you turn it to safe mode and lose the dogs, you can actually make progress. Building ships in Space Engineers is immensely satisfying, requiring forethought, intentional block placement, and testing. The blocks they have are just plain cool, and each one offers a level of complexity and functionality that I find other games of this genre lack. The logic is fun and easy to use too. It almost made me forget how infuriating some of the previously mentioned content is.All of that said, I can say that I'm happy I bought it, though my negative recommendation will still stand as long as all that good stuff remains buried under so many half-baked and frustrating features.Original post:It's raw, complicated, and unpolished for a game already in development for several years. I spent 10 hours confirming that the crafting system is cyclical, meaning you can't start from scratch, and if you run out of power, which every thing in the game is trying to make happen, you will float into space and die without a single action you can take to rectify the situation.Pretty graphics, great physics, needs a metric shipload (see what I did there?) of work before I can recommend this, even at $8 on sale. Seriously, go play StarMade."
