,Recommended,244850,32985925,Posted: 29 June,all,Native Faith,"Space Engineers. Jeese, I've spent countless hours on my friend's private server just mining, building, and mining some more and it's a strange experience everytime I do it. I'd say I've spent more nights playing Space Engineers feeling my time was ""wasted"" rather than feeling like I had fun. Then I come back the next night.At first, it's pretty boring. Survival is easy, and creative mode simply doesn't appeal to me. There is no ""challenge"" laid out  like there would be in other similar games. No real enemies to harass you or siege your creations and spur you to action. In reality, your greatest enemy is yourself and your faulty, lazy, shortsighted designs.You crash your first miner into an asteroid, or god forbid, your painstakingly build space station and you start to try to add safety features, redudant systems, repair systems, etc etc. You start to add more industry and conveyors, storage and sorters to your base to make construction of new ships more efficient. And then finally, you crash your miner again into your station and you scrap the whole thing and start laying down large plans and designs, ambitious projects that take hours upon hours to build, just so you don't wreck it again. And then you wreck it, or your friend wrecks it, or a bug wrecks it and you find yourself toiling away at it again.Honestly, that's what it's been like for me. Build bigger, smarter, bigger again, and then wonder how you can do it better next time or make it look cleaner, nicer to show off to friends.The hurdle is getting past that first phase of wanting an objective or something to ""do"". It's a game without challenge or difficulty and it's a game that eats up all of your hours of freetime, but... It's also a game that's fulfilling on it's own sometimes and even thrilling in those short moments where you realize how much you risk steering through a dangerous situation.The best example I could give is secondhand, from my friend who was piloting everything he owned, literally perhaps a hundred man-hours of cost from him and the rest of us, into the orbit of a planet. He wanted to keep it in orbit so he could use it to establish a new station, but had gone further than he had expected. He was too late on the inertial dampeners and he could feel the gravity of the planet working against the controls, the atmopshere sapping the efficiency of the thrusters meant for space travel. Everyone playing on that server just hearing about this shared some of the sheer terror he felt as he struggled to save his ship and were geuinely relieved to hear he made it out of orbit again.That's the truly the best part of the game, in my opinion, and if you can get behind that, I'd recommend Space Engineers. If you thought that it sounds boring and you want♥♥♥♥♥♥to shoot at, things to attack you, and level ups and skill ups and money, etc... Don't buy this game. Simple as that."
