,Recommended,244850,13441249,"Posted: 18 December, 2014",all,AaronLee,"When playing paid alpha games I always like to live by the rule of; ""Don't buy itif it's not fun yet.""Space Engineers suffers from some bugs but, thanks to the recent string or weekly releases, it has stabilized significantly. Multiplayer performance has been hit and miss over time, but when it works MP is a blast, even if to just get your creations some exposure in a community besides the workshop. The mod integration is already seamless, though currently VERY limitted in scope.Being based on havoc, which any good gamer knows is not a physics simulator but a things'wot'go-fast-and-explode simulator, the game's physics for everything BUT collisions are very wonky. The game seems to be aware of this and tries its best to show off its superior collision and object damage physics by making your creations self-destruct spontaneously and without reason. This is especially true in multiplayer but has, in recent updates subsided. Most of the unique building features that the Havoc engine previously dissaproved of (and showed this by showing off its amazing collision physics) are much more stable.Keen Software House have shown responsiveness in the past and the legacy of glitchiness now largely relegated to Space Engineers' past shows this. With any luch, the game that is launched from this alpha will be truly stupendous.Until the, it's fun as-is."
