,Recommended,244850,9783511,"Posted: 10 April, 2014",all,USMCG_Deranged,"For those that say this is similar to Minecraft wouldn't be completely wrong. However, this is what I would consider Minecraft for adults or those that prefer a beautiful atmosphere i.e. highly polished graphics, and it's still in Alpha by the way.I had been watching this game grow for a couple weeks or so, but already knew I wanted to play it eventually. Minecraft was not for me; hated the graphics and monotonous activity of digging, hacking, or slashing to build NES 8-bit communities. I didn't hate all of it though, I thought the addition of adding in traps was a nice touch, but too little too late for me as I had already stopped playing it (for the entire 4 hours I did play).Space Engineers is just amazing in what it is and has accomplished. A space atmosphere that makes me feel as though this is exactly how I would move if I were in space. The building is simplistic, yet very in depth at the same time. My only complaint is of a personal one in that my computer setup is my central hub to everything electronic and I use a very small keyboard that uses ""alt"" keys for things like DELETE and HOME, etc. So, I bought a brand new gaming keyboard and couch desk just so I could plunk many more hours into this game comfortably.Updates are weekly and sometimes daily even as the devs continue to polish this game into something their fanbase wants to play instead of the AAA companies making a game that puts cash in the bank. The devs listen to their customers and are transforming what is already an amazing experience into something more.I highly recommend picking this up while it is still in Alpha so that you can see what it is now and what it will later become. For anyone that enjoys turning on some music and zoning out in space while creating, destroying, or just exploring this game will definitely fit the bill.Also, it has GUNS, ROCKETS, MISSILES, etc!!!! What Marine or otherwise insane civilian doesn't like shooting things and watching them be eviscerated?!"
,Recommended,244850,9795179,"Posted: 12 April, 2014",all,Roasty McToasty,"----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------Much TL;DR, it's a game about building spaceships and space stations in an asteroid field by mining the asteroids. Worth a shot if you like building stuff, mining stuff, or just blowing the pulp out of big things in space.If you're looking for scores, scroll down near the bottom. Otherwise, keep reading if you're the patient kind of guy (Be warned though, this review came out stupidly long)----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------Armed with a game engine hailing from 2012's Miner Wars 2081, Keen Software House takes the Mining/Survival/Creative concept popularized by Minecraft and similar games, and puts it in outer space. An interesting combination, certainly, that many of us have perhaps thought of at least once; ""What if there was a game which allowed me to build Minecraft-style, but in space?"".Using the knowledge and game engine applied in Miner Wars, KSH set out to create something to that end, and Space Engineers was the result. Summed up in one long sentence, the game basically puts you in the shoes of an astronaut lost in deep space; with no hope of rescue, you must analyze your surroundings, and use your engineering knowledge to mine the surrounding asteroids for resources, set up a base and protect yourself from environmental hazards.Space Engineers is, in all its glory, the sum of its parts. Its parts being detailed below:Mining and manufacturing: One way to get anywhere in the long run is to analyze the asteroid fields, mine the dozen or so different ores and minerals, run them through a refinery structure and assemble the resulting ingots into parts, with which to build new stations and ships.Piracy and warfare: However, when you're a bit more established, you may wish to explore the other way, which was made available in a recent update: weapons manufacture and subsequently piracy & warfare. From time to time, NPC ships will fly near your asteroid field, and when they do it's your choice to leave them be, or take what's (un)rightfully yours. Similarily, the manufacture of weapons allows you to start doing battle against other people, building ships and outfitting them with guns and ammo. While ship dogfighting is, currently, the main form of feasible warfare in Space Engineers, there is no lack of hand-weapons, which lend an FPS aspect to the game as well, which works seamlessly with the dynamic construction system, allowing people to build battle arenas and things of the like, which also brings me to the next point...Creative construction: Another major selling point for Space Engineers is the ability to build without limit. Space is endless, and so are the possibilities in creative mode, as evidenced by the monolithic constructions found on the Steam Workshop.In fact, even the survival mode allows you to explore the reaches of your mind once you've got a proper factory up and running, as the vast overabundance of minerals pose no availibility issues.However, like all game concepts on good and bad, there are things about the game that certain players will find annoying. This is, however, subjective and things some people find incredibly annoying might not have the same effect on other players. Allow me to elaborate...Logistics is currently an issue, to say the least. Cargo holds do not work properly, conveyors are disabled, and transfer of cargo from one ship to another is as of yet impossible without use of the astronaut as a middleman. Further, the big ship gun turrets are also disabled and unusable. There are a number of issues beyond these which I cannot remember at the time of writing this review, but that is irrelevant, as the devs are working tirelessly to correct issues and add functionality. In fact, thus far, there's been an update every week, with but a few misses. Can you name a big-label AAA title that does or did that after it's premature release as a public alpha? Didn't think so.This review has gone on for long enough now, and if you've read the entire thing, you are a patient person. I value patience, and thus, I commend you. Below is a conclusion.So, what are my thoughts on this game? Let's break it down to an easy 1-10 scale. Keep in mind that these are based on opinions and may not fully reflect the actual score a professional reviewer would've given it.Gameplay: 8 or 9. Depends on what aspects of the game you like. Me, I like being creative, I like sci-fi, and I like big things. Big vehicles especially. Oh, and space.Visuals: 6, 7, or 8. Depends on what you look at and what settings you're playing on. While the game engine is, as mentioned up at the top of this page, lifted from Keen Software House's 2012 title Miner Wars 2081, it is only the asteroids that are left behind from that game, as everything man-made is modelled and textured from scratch, and the relative quality of those pieces are dependant on what your render settings are at: if it's on 'normal', they might look lacking to the eye, but on 'extreme', they actually look quite good. The problem is that unless you have a top-tier PC, you may have trouble getting 50 or 60 FPS out of the game on 'extreme'.Audio: 5 or 6. Depends on if you value noise over realism. For this game KSH have decided on a realistic approach for the gameplay, with proper space dynamics representation. However, they went away from the realism on the audio; in real life, space is silent. It is impossible by nature to project sound in the gasless empty of space, yet you can clearly and from a distance hear factories and tools working as if you were on a planet bathing in gas. Of course, with all this said, it'd be quite boring to have literally everything be completely silent, and if you'd want that, it is as easy as muting the sound or using software to make sound more real and muffle it. As for the sound itself, it's fairly realistic, and the game has its own music soundtrack. Nothing hugely memorable, but it's there nonetheless.User Interface: 6. Basically, the HUD is the regular old bar at the bottom of the screen that represents what items you have hotlinked. There's also a window that shows a few stats about what you're doing, how much you're carrying, how much energy you've left, etc. The inventory itself and things related to such is fairly more complicated and not exactly intuitive. However, it gets easier when you've played for a while.Okay, this review has gone on for a stupidly long while now. Again, I commend you if you read the whole thing.Thanks for reading, be sure to vote this up if you thought it was helpful enough!"
