76561198009512192,Recommended,244850,10106442,"Posted: 13 May, 2014",all,Treysss,"Wonderful game; well worth the current price tag ($20) to get hold of either creative or survival mode. Getting both together -- in addition to multiplayer and the workshop -- is fantastic.""Space Engineers is inspired by reality and by how things work. Think about modern-day NASA technology extrapolated 60 years into the future. Space Engineers strives to follow the laws of physics and doesn't use technologies that wouldn't be feasible in the near future. "" Try to keep this quote (from the game description) in mind; in Space Engineers, you'll find propulsion systems, guns, explosives, etc...but you won't be finding force fields or warp drives (at least not yet; there are some monster modding opportunities with this game, however).With physics as realistic as they can be within the limits of the game engine, this game also works wonderfully to help children understand principles they might not grasp so easily out of just a textbook. Float in space with no stabilizers to keep you in place and shoot a gun...sure, the bullets go forward, but you also go backward. Put engines on the back of a ship to push you forward...that's fine...but try to stop without engines on the front to provide 'reverse acceleration', and you're in trouble.Okay...I've run on far too long. Short: this game is far more than worth the price tag. The devs really do listen to players' thoughts and opinions and take them into account. New updates each week, with new pieces or updates to make gameplay smoother. Just buy it already.(Also check out space engineers on youtube to see some of the amazing things others have created...find something you like? Download it off the workshop and play with it yourself, or just blow it up!)"
