76561197971438700,Recommended,244850,29533754,Posted: 27 January,all,Kether11,"I love this game. I've put up a persistent server that nobody plays on, but I don't care. I play on it, and I have a blast.  I like building things.  I want to get into the scripting part.  But I don't want my LCD panels to say Hello World.Here's my issue: There's no overarching ""Why.""""Survival!"" you say?I navigate my planetary lander down to the ground, press ""j"" to take off my helmet, and I'm done.  I've survived..  I can stand there till the cows come home, and I'm  surviving; I've survived; Game Over; Power Off.Everything else--planets, moons, spiders, connectors, masses, that 15MH battery, welder upgrade what?  that's  just fluff.  All I have to do is stand there and the game is DONE.I need the ""Why.""  I need a goal.  I need a reason to go beyond just standing there, surviving with my helmet off, taking in an admittedly glorious sunrise with the half-lit crescent of a huge planet on the horizon.""So build things!""So--why?I would like to direct the devs' attention to Avorion: a recent alpha release of a space sim with *nothing near* the amazing capabilities of Space Engineers.But they have a story, and they have a ""Why.""  And even though you have to play *as a ship,* and the physics and building are primitive in comparison, the game still compels: there's a quest to undertake; a mission to fulfill, and it's addictive as hell.I am certain that the issues in SE with wheels, rotors, and pistons --especially in dedicated multiplayer--will be resolved, given time and some attention.  But--for me at least-- unless there's an overarching purpose to avail myself of everything SE has to offer, I'm going to leave ninety percent of it untouched, and I will stand there, surviving, Hello World on my LCDs, taking in a glorious sunrise on the earth-like planet, with a misty moon setting in the distance.So I want more.  I want everything I can accomplish in Space Engineers to steer me toward some glorious heroism.  I want to be able to save the freaking galaxy if I could only just--engineer something good enough to do the perfect job at the appropriate time."
