,Recommended,244850,8597961,"Posted: 6 January, 2014",all,Linkoo0,THIS GAME IS AWESOME
,Recommended,244850,13949769,"Posted: 11 January, 2015",all,Utildayael,"Early Access Review - 1/11/15Space Engineers is a fun game on the outside and very complex on the inside. While many compare it to Minecraft, I think the comparison ends at ""uses blocks"" and ""is in the same genre"" as that is really about the it of it. The game uses grids to determine ""groups"" of blocks into ships [small/large] as well as space stations! You can piece together a ship and actually fly it complete with physics and block damage if you say... accidently ram the ship into an asteroid at full thrust.The game offers both creative mode and survival but, as of this writing, survival mode is still very much a work in progress. The two keys to survival currently is that your suit has a power limit such that you can't  just stand outside forever [but it's easy to charge back up] and the fact that you have to actually get the materials to build the items you want. Items are built in stages and require a variety of components that you weld together as long as they are in your inventory. Larger objects require far more weight [yes, these blocks have volume and weight!] but you can built construction ships with multiple welders [and waaaay more storage] to take the place of you and your blowtorch. Most items have construction stages so you can see them ""progress"" from a steel frame to a working block as you apply the parts. The building works very well and deconstruction works similiar, except you use a grinder and you GET items instead of place items such that ships and other things can be recycled.But wait, there's more! Cargo ships and derelects litter the universe free for the taking. Some have guns and will try to aggressively kill you, but free none-the-less!Creative mode on the other hand is what you would expect. Unlimited resources and all blocks are fully built when placed. Add to this the glorious symmetry mode which allows you to mirror X/Y/Z axis [user selectable!] and you have, imho, one of the best creative building modes around. Most blocks can be rotated in 90 degree increments so a simple ramp can be turned in any direction or even upside down. For those who like to build, the benefits of this are readily apparent! The other dynamic Keen has introduced is that of copy/paste and blueprints. Once you create your super ship of doom you can copy it to the clipboard and make it into a blueprint. This blueprint can be pasted into the world as many times as you like in Creative, turned into a Workshop item to share with other users, or even attached to a projector in a survival world to project a hologram of the design and allow the player to weld all the pieces together! This is an amazing system and works very well.Finally, this game has stellar Steam Workshop support. Aside from being able to blueprint ships and stations to share, there is also very solid modding support and the modding scene for Space Engineers is already going strong with no additions and changes to the game including change game rules [like max speed] and adding entirely new blocks and entities to the game. Keen does a great job of providing a whole slew of things thus far and this only expands it further and compliments their work.Overall, this is a wonderful game and easily worth the price. The only caveat I have is for hardcore survival players, you might get bored with the current state as it is really quite easy to stay alive and gather resources to the point of having a massive surplus of everything. This is a heavy WIP and Keen notes they have many plans for the future to enhance this area. Given their update history [often!] I would expect to see some serious changes in the coming months. Keen has been great at updating the game and listening to the playerbase so I'd advise checking the updates page and the forums for the current state of the game as it changes [usually for the bettter] often on a weekly basis."
76561198025288622,Recommended,244850,18480186,"Posted: 14 October, 2015",all,prometheo,"Space engineers is a great space sandbox.  The Keen Software House team has done a great job building out this game from what was originally quite modest, but inspiring in its potential, to something which now is becoming quite formidable... and still inspiring for the potential of what is right around the corner!I think you can make of this game what you want of it, but personally it inspires me to solve problems and figure out how to ""get it done"" in the face of obstacles that, arbitrary as they may be (don't like it, go play creative!) are still challenging.Recent story: I was out in just my suit, naked if you will, scrounging for resources, looking for a **** cobalt patch, and I was around 40% power left in my suit and said to myself, you can check out that next rock before heading back.  So, I power up my jets to get to 100 m/s and then go adrift to preserve power, drop out of my approach and check out the rock I came to.  Catalogued the best resources in my GPS waypoint for it and spotted my base, about 20 clicks away now.  Mind you I had already gotten several dings of ""energy low"" - signaling that I'm below 25% power, but I figured I was still good.  So, I launch back to full speed, on course to hit home with a few percent left after my decelleration burn.  Worked out perfectly, except that when I get there, my base had gone dark because my refinery burned up all the uranium in my reactor.  So before recharging I would need to grab some refined uranium from the refinery itself.  As the last seconds ticked away, I put the fuel in the reactor and heard things power back on... but my power ran out at that exact moment.  I was stuck, but because my medical station was next to the reactor, I could reach it from my paralyzed state and recharge my suit.  I don't think it gets closer than that!Anyway, basically legos in space... with the always present risk of bodily harm or (since recently) pirate raids.  Good luck!"
