76561198038454355,Recommended,244850,9949934,"Posted: 27 April, 2014",all,AegisKnight,"Let me just begin by saying that as of writing this, I have thrown just under 100 hours at this game, and I still come back almost daily to see what else I can engineer into existence.Where Minecraft excelled at grabbing my attention, this game has not only grabbed it but held it and continues to impress me. In some ways, it is similar to the concept that Minecraft began with its sandbox 'square' world, however Space Engineers not only took this idea and expanded on it, they blew it completely out of the water. The complete sandbox nature of this game may sometimes get tedious (as of currently there is no actual goal or objective), offering a downside to the single player aspect, the multiplayer is always enjoyable; assuming you have or know enjoyable people to play with.The other great part about this game is... well, the development team. Keen Software House are more than I ever could have hoped for in a dev team. They are constantly acknowledging the fanbase, always hotfixing issues often only hours after an issue arises, and their dedication to giving the game a huge chunk of content weekly (not tweaks and fixes - I'm talking new items by the dozen), is reason evermore to consider getting this game. Every Friday I log in and check their website purely to see what I will get to mess around with this week. Keen Software House has earned themselves a fan for life here, as I see it.Like all sandbox games, you're almost free to do whatever you will wish within the limits of reason. That's what makes this game so perfect. Its genre and style go perfectly hand in hand, and the realism that space can offer in terms of what you can conceptualize and believe are perfect. Each new item that gets added can have sometimes hundreds of possible uses. Personally, I find this game at its best when playing with other players who each bring their own ideas to the table.""But what if you use glass for this!?""""Stick the rotor on another rotor and your piston will stop smashing your base apart!""""What if you put the cockpit further to the back and made the front into an ammo hold?""What people often fail to see and miss in a sandbox game like Minecraft is, ""Once I build my house, and get all the best gear, and kill the dragon...? What then?""The beauty of this game is that because of its physics engine, and the fact that you can incorporate moving parts, there is literally ALWAYS something more to try and build. I have maps with prototype after prototype of things that I tried and failed, only to refine the idea after running tests on its weak points, on what it should do better, and how I could do it faster and cheaper.This game forces you to be an engineer. You must constantly be looking for ways to make your construction cheaper to make, easier to build and more efficient. There will always be something to do in this game, and personally, I'm always looking for value for money, replayability and interesting challenges in any game I purchase. This game hits all three marks. I'll leave you with this quote, which also happens to be in the game.Engineers like to solve problems. If there are no problems handily available, they will create their own problems - Scott Adams"
76561198080553055,Recommended,244850,9955231,"Posted: 27 April, 2014",all,Jordan,"Buy it, just do it I would play £15 just for the music but the game is sick as well you're in space and basically do whatever the f*** you feel like 10/10"
,Recommended,244850,9963330,"Posted: 28 April, 2014",all,Emitz,"The game is pretty great already, but as early access, there's a lot of stuff missing. Every update adds some great things, but there are some things I would like to touch on, particularly on the survival mode that was just added. Most of the hours ive put into the game have been into survival.Simply put, its too easy. There just arent enough threats to you. Other than asteroids storms of varying intensity, there are no threats to you. Parking behind an asteroid and mining it completely nullifies the threat the storms pose. Uranium is easy to find, and cargo ships can be easily scavenged for parts, as they are all derelicts flung into the system with powered engines. Truthfully, in survival mode you have a greater chance of killing yourself with your jetpack than dying to asteroids. Hopefully they add some NPCs to cargo ships, or add some type of pirates in survival that attack you if you stay in one place for too long. As of now, survival is basically a drawn out creative mode. Fun, but its missing the critical 'threat' element, that is usually typical for a survival modeTurning off either asteroids/asteroid storms and cargo ships increases difficulty as much as it breaks immersion, so i dont recommend that.Great game, and i still recommend that, but I bought the game once I saw survival mode was added, and wanted to let people know what I experienced."
