,Recommended,244850,24794349,"Posted: 9 August, 2016",all,MichaelJG02,"READ TO THE END TO SEE WHY I RECOMMENDED THIS!This review is going to be hard to write, because of the current state this game is in. I will have to split the review into a few sections to accommodate for the different states it has such as STABLE branch and DEVELOPMENT branch.STABLE Branch:The stable branch is well, stable, sorta. I have had only 2 crashes in the stable branch, and that was from me overloading the game on my underpowered system (i5 6400, 12GB RAM, Intel HD 530.) I have had lower FPS in the stable branch, on the Lone Survivor scenario, I get around 19fps when first spawn, after letting stuff load for a minute it is at 19fps. If you like having your game stable, but don't really care about low fps, then play in the stable branch. One thing that is bad about this is that it only gets updated about twice a month. One update on Thursday and a little patch on the following Friday.DEV Branch:The dev branch is a good branch if you really want to help test things out for KSH (Keen Software House.) When I first loaded into a Lone Survivor scenario, I was greeted with 23fps, much more playable. Still choppy, but I digress. The dev branch gets updated every Thursday for the main bugs fixes and additions, and on Fridays, a small patch is sent to help out with some bugs until the next Thursday. To my surprise and to yours possibly, is I have had no crashes on the Dev Branch.My Thoughts on the Game:I love Space Engineers, I really do, but this game has been in the Alpha status for almost 3 years now. I think they should have fixed stuff like the netcode, pistons and rotors, and some other things, not add the Planets first. I get that you should do what the community wants to have in the game, because that brings more people, but in my opinion, when the community said that they wanted, Keen should have addressed this by saying ""We will add planets, after we fix everything else"" That would have been a lot smarter on their end because the netcode is still broke. But with the game in state, I cannot recommend this game to those that expect the game to just work well on their machines. This game isn't optimized very well for systems like mine, or those that have i7 5820k's and 980Ti's. I will put a Thumbs up on this to recommend this to people that can deal with the bugs, and want to see this game grow.  DO NOT however buy this if you think you are going to get the best experience ever. You will most likely get a decent experience. If you can't stand to play this game after awhile because of it's current state, set the game down, and wait a few months to see if it is better. This game will be good when everything is worked out."
