76561198042160921,Recommended,244850,13013142,"Posted: 19 November, 2014",all,bilboswaginz,"This is my first review and I feel that I have played enough to know just about everything this game has to offer and how it can be improved and what is broken and ect. I will break it down into lists and throw my two cents at it.I'll start with mods...Now I personally do not like mods because as a builder I like to keep things vanilla and solve problems that would normally be fixed through mods. Though I must admit this game has a very large mod selection and if your a player who loves that kind of stuff then you will love this aspect of the game. The mods do not hurt the game for vanilla ♥♥♥♥ like myself but if you like to go ham with mods then go for it this game will let you and don't let others tell you any better. ;)Physics engine....For an indy game this physics engine is pretty solid. Though the game does have its limits so if you crash two deathstars together your going to have a bad time lol. One of the recent updates improved armor protection which was done really well in my opinion. The only thing I feel that needs to be changed is an improvment to the cockpits damage resistance but overall the game engine is very well executed.Building....The building controls are really good for a game like this. several tools are available for you to take advantage of and use to improve your designs. The symmetry tool is problably the most useful tool in the game! This tool pretty much is a builder's(like myself) wet dream come true. Also, with a creative mode you can build to your heart(or your computer ram's lel) desire. So if your creative like with legos or other builder games then why haven't you bought this game yet?Networking....Unfortunatly the hardest thing to code in any game, it is no suprise that this games multiplayer is under par with other games like minecraft or other server based game. Most of which is due to outside problems like peoples internet or the Servers ping. IMO I think Keen should invest into a community server that has good specs for people to play on together. Set up a defende no pvp zone trade station in the middle and see what becomes of it. One of the hardest things to code that this game is going to one day have to figure out is how to sync a none host player with a moving ship so you don't lag out of in in multiplayer. Other then that the networking of this game is somwhat average and the developers seem to be pushing big fixes toward it as they seem to know this is the games weakest link.PVP/MiningWhere there is resources to mine you can hear the shattering of someones ship and the chat boxes exsploding with rage. people like to complain about the game being pvp based. I can't argue with that though it pretty much is PvP based. What I can argue with is that the pvp ruins the game. Now any game with no challange and happy go miny is just a dead end aka farmville 2.0 space edition. If this game had no PvP then we can just rename the game toMeteor Miner: In space, no one can hear you drill. The PvP is problably one of the most important aspects of the game. With the game's unique game engine and blocks you can create some pretty sophisticated weapons. Everything from Scout drones to guided warheads the sky(or as I must say, the stars) are the limit. The same goes with Mining, it is a very important part of the game and everyone must start somewhere. A good group of about 5 people with 2 dedicated miners, and 3 builders can have a large base(with defences) and a small attack vessel going in about 2 hours if they keep at it.Last but not least......Game difficulty(survival)Now, personally for myself I dont find the game difficult (hurr 600+ hours :P), but to others I feel some things in the game are overlooked and either people don't understand or just don't care(giant blocks with missle launchers QQ). Some features of the game make you look past others and you could go on your way to make a ship that looks cool but not actually work. Which if thats what your going for is looks then by all means go for it, im talking about players who build these giant ships and hold shift building turrets and call it survival ready. Now, where am I getting with all this? well it all comes down to two sides of the game of Space Engineers, Creative and Survival. Survival is no doubt the game mode that is going to♥♥♥♥♥♥you off if your new. To really have a grip of survival you have to take into account everything. every turret, every generator, every cargo block. Turrets use ammo, Gens use uranium(solar Panal Master Race), and cargos hold all the goods, But for your ship to actually function properly it all MUST be connected in some way. Conveyor blocks are the most useful in doing this job. All blocks with a type of cargo space has a door like opening on them. This is a slot to connect other blocks with slots or conveyors to connect to other blocks with such slots. generators connected to cargos will bring in uranuim if its avaliable in the cargo blocks. Turrets must be connected to cargo blocks in some way to pull available ammo from said cargo blocks. Once you get used to this feature you will be on your way to creating ships that look good AND can work on survival.(wouldn't that be cool huh?)Overall....Space engineers is the most developed game of its class. Even though it is still an alpha it feels to be more of an early beta, but that is for you to judge thats just my opinion. Overall space engineers has the potential to be a huge hit and if the devs keep putting stuff into the game to improve then it can only get better. Time will tell what this game turns into.In the mean time, have fun, stop griefing with no creativity(im talking about you people who put waves of warheads on ships <.<), and just build on :P.I R8 8/8"
