,Recommended,244850,13767761,"Posted: 1 January, 2015",all,Consul Testiclës of Scrotum,"At the time of this writing, I have 262 hours on record with this game. I've been playing it basically since it came out. I bought it when a friend of mine recommended it, and since we'd had hours of fun playing on modded minecraft servers, I figured I'd take his word for it.Space Engineers was pretty feature-bare at the time, but it did have a formula for success. To give you an overview of the game mechanics: ships and stations are built on a minecraft-like grid, but everything moves realistically in 3D space with an actual physics engine. Blocks have actual deformation models for when they get shot or banged up, and asteroids are voxel-based, so mining isn't based on one-meter cubes.The game has come a LONG way since it's beginning, and if you're wary because it's early access or technically still alpha, don't be. Keen has been very good about implementing meaningful updates EVERY Thursday (most recently we also got a long string of bugfixing). It also has a modding API with a very active workshop, and a very active user base that Keen is good about listening to - half of the features currently in the game were derived from user feedback. Actually, I just learned that, as of today, actual programming is in the game now.The game is still in Alpha, for good reason. Some people claim to have difficulty with multiplayer, because the netcode isn't stellar. It's a LOT better than it used to be, just not perfect yet. The game is a bit demanding on hardware - again, it's been optimized, and my GPU no longer climbs its way to 70 degrees to play it, but you'll probably have a ♥♥♥♥♥♥ time on low-end hardware, and even people who normally don't have problems will have slowdowns in large ships or busy areas.Personally, I spend most of my time playing solo in creative, but the community is robust so I never feel lonely. Creative lacks for much of a direction so far - much like minecraft in the early days, it's just a sandbox with limitations after you've got a good setup - but they recently added procedural generation of asteriods and random implementation of community-built derelict ships. Multiplayer can be fun, there are servers both public and private, but like I said, some people claim to have trouble.If you're the type of person who enjoys sandbox games, either solo or with friends, and particularly if you enjoyed minecraft, I think Space Engineers is a game for you. It's on sale ($9.99, normally $19.99) as I write this, and there are rumors circulating that there's going to be a price hike in the future, so now is the time to buy if you're on the fence. In 260+ hours, I've gotten more than $10 of enjoyment out of this game, and can't recommend it enough."
