,Recommended,244850,11611167,"Posted: 8 August, 2014",all,Kask,"With the introduction of planets I've come back to re-write this review.This update, while although cutting my performance in half, is completely amazing. Planets completely change how the game is played, from surviving in an unforgiving environment of physics and engineering to travelling the depths of space and exploring new worlds.The planets are procedurally generated then given a nice human touch. This means the developers go back in and make some nice memorable areas that are sure to stick with you. Along with the hand crafted-ness what gives it a nice touch is that the resources that spawn on planets are random, which means diffrent worlds will have different types of ores in their locations, even if the planet is the same template as another.The introduction of planets creates a nice flow of the game, giving you more of a reason to create new, more useful vehicles. By default, in survival, you start off entering a planet with a lander. Usually you'll want to stabilize the lander and you will float in mid air, able to see your surroundings. Sometimes you'll start off on the dark side of the planet meaning you'll either have the wait for day time or fly towards the light. Once you can actually see the ground one of the best things to do is find an ice field (Looks like water, isn't water..... yet). From there you'll be able to mine all the ice you need when you make hydrogen thrusters (Used later in the game). Once you safely land you'll want to start constructing a renewable energy source, to do this you'll need solar panels, and depending on how fast your day/night cycle is you'll want to do this quickly. From there you need to find ores, refine them, and begin on your main base. Try to set up a base that has automated defenses and will be able to manage on its own when you are away from it. Once you have a nice base setup, you may want to work on making a spaceship. To do this you'll need hydrogen thrusters. I recommend you do a hydrogen thruster setup on the bottom of your ship and ion thrusters everywhere else. (Except maybe one or two small hydrogen thrusters in the back.) Before you go on your journey in space you'll want to make sure you have a surplus of hydrogen, because if you run out of hydrogen you're doomed. Once you make it to space you can setup a space station, deploy a few satelites, or come up with some ideas of your own.This is just a fraction of the possibilities of this game.Multiplayer, while currently not stable, is still enjoyable with a few friends. I recommend you and some friends get into even teams, start on the same planet, and go to war. You can develop atmospheric vehicles to deploy explosive payloads, design ICBMs to annihilate your foes, and come up with other devastating weapons.The community for Space Engineers can somtimes be a bit harsh, but are for the most part extremely nice and respectable people. Join in on the forums atKeenSWH.comand be sure to take part in conversations, and you may even find yourself a new friend.Let alone the vanilla (un-modded) version of the game being awesome, the collection of mods the community has made is truely outstanding. I recommend you check out the Space Engineers workshop and be sure to download all the great mods there are out there.Overall, I rate Space Engineers 9.1/10. I would make it 10/10 but the optimization is poor, but don't let that deter you. This game has infinite potential after it is more optimized and multiplayer becomes more stable.As a last statement, if you love open world, sandbox games, in which you get to use your imagination to create things you never could before, and use them in entertaining and delightful ways, and do all of that in a combination of space and planetary engineering, then this game is for you. Space Engineers has the potential to become one of the best space-themed games in a long time."
