76561198024500931,Recommended,244850,21259625,"Posted: 16 February, 2016",all,Melburd,"Reviewing Space Engineers comes with a bit of a problem, because as much as I want to give it a glowing review, I'm still bitter about the solid month it took the dev team to finally get around to fixing their♥♥♥♥♥♥after the Dx11 update. I have almost a thousand hours logged on this f*cking game. Do you have any idea how much masturbation I had to do to fill that void?All jokes aside though... Yes. This is a game worth buying. Because in Space Engineers you can design and build a fully detailed million ton space battleship and use it to glass a solar system. If that right there didn't sell it for you, I don't know what will. That isn't just ambition, that is insane.You're an engineer. In space- the ultimate sandbox, being pretty much a near perfect void 'n all. Aside from the bits that aren't. Like most sandboxes its pretty empty, and enemies are surprisingly scarce- the occasional AI attack, or juicy NPC ships to steal if you're feeling piritical. You mine resources and build♥♥♥♥♥♥ pretty much any♥♥♥♥♥♥you could imagine you'd want to build in space and yes that is rather reminiscent of minecraft, isn't it? But minecraft never let you play with a million tons of space battleship so the comparison is rather void. Nevertheless, it is worth saying that this is more creativity toy than game. Play with friends. Like most sandbox games you will probably want to mod it a lot, which is fine because the modding community seems to be way more into the project than the damned dev team behind it.As the astute reader may have gathered by the opening of this review, it seems that for every step the dev team take there are another three steps to the side before the entire thing crashes, dies and needs more frantic hotfixes. With pretty much every early access game you expect the bug reports section of the forum to be by far the biggest, but DAMN. Optimization? Eventually someone will get around to it, but I suspect they'll be the one that drew a short straw. This is a game that literally tries to simulate a solar system. If you want to run it, a decent rig is utterly essential. Play it for a hundred hours and you are going to encounter issues that will make the game unplayable. Sadly, that is just how things are. Each fix brings more issues that need fixing, and so far this seems to be a never ending cycle.On the other hand, if you can get past that or suffer through it, what you have is any scifi nerd's wet dream. You can build your own fleets and square them off against likeminded others, if the netcode holds up. You can claim (or crash onto) a whole world and defend it against waves of AI enemies, if you have the ambition. You can go on the forums and complain that the game isn't realistic enough, if you're a tosser.Something for almost everyone!"
