76561198091467820,Recommended,244850,9868199,"Posted: 19 April, 2014",all,Solumn Trade,"If you're a fan of Minecraft, but want something a little more robust and a lot more sci-fi, then this is the game for you. I suppose the best comparison would be that if Minecraft were Legos, then Space Engineers is an Erector set. Instead of a humble crafting bench that forges together the materials you've pulled out of the ground, you can make sprawling factories that pump out building supplies, fueled by an extensive mining operation that can grind away entire astroids the size of mountains; so long as you're ambitious enough. More content is being added rapidly, and I firmly believe that this style of game will set the new standards for open-world sandboxes.There is a few negatives though. As always, there are the trolls, so you may want to hide your ship or station if you plan on playing with the puplic. (Some jerk spawned in and rammed a naturally spawning ship that I had captured. Unfortunately, everyone who spawns in gets a 'rescue ship' with which to survive with, or in the case of trolls ram with.) Also, the maps, although larger than from the game Rust, feels kind of small even on the largest settings because of the ability to travel at high velocities, and due to being in space you can see pretty much the entire map. However, although astroids have quite a far draw distance, ships and stations thankfully do not. So despite the map feeling small, there are plenty of places to hide, including inside the larger astroids.That aside, it has its fair share of self-made humorous moments, brought on by the game's physics engine. One time I attempted to move one ship with another by locking onto it. Unfortunately, the fuel ran dry just as I was about finished. With no fuel, the ship couldn't steady itself and thus the two ships were locked into a spinning death spiral. Unable to stop it, I had to bail. I tried to bring fuel to it, but the two ships were spinning too fast and I banged against it and died. Solumnly, I could not help but laugh as both ships spiraled off into space, never to return...one of which was my friend's. He, of coarse, was laughing.)This game rewards ingenuity, makes failure spectacular, and keeps you comming back for more."
