76561198063245160,Recommended,244850,19167162,"Posted: 19 November, 2015",all,illPosedProblem,"Fun and largely unconstrained block-builder, with physics simulation being the most fun and limiting (due computation cost) feature.First, the good bits:- the ability to block-build stations, large ships, small fighters, torpedoes, automated asteroid sentries, sensor/comm networks, cargo ships and many, many other things. It compares favourably with a heavily-modded Minecraft in terms of creative freedom.- physics simulation: all objects either thrust or collide to change motion states (or are affected by a gravity field). Player-built gravity-generators interact in a somewhat limited fashion, but still make for fun gameplay.- fun weapons, multiplayer, faction/ownership systems; also detection ranges, well-made antenna/comm systems with limited ranges.- well-implemented surveying, mining, storage, transfer, sorting, refining and building. A pleasure to carefully design a large base or ship, use a few resources to build its skeleton, then mindlessly mine, refine and build it over the course of a few hours. Creative mode available as well if you don't have a movie handy.- programming and display blocks: you can code within the game, and have ships and bases act according to your program. Display blocks can be made to readily expose information, from text to 2d maps.- modding: well-made, alive and well.- support: constant updates. As befits an alpha, more focused on adding new features than bugfixing and optimisation.- pre-made scenarios and world customisation (infinite worlds, pirates, travelling cargo or military ships, asteroid showers) make for quick game starts.Now, for the bad bits:- physics simulation: due to the large quantity of simulated objects, and the current computation limits, the game can be quite slow. The main limiting factor in building designs is the framerates, and it's just sad to have to abandon the station built piece by piece over a few months because it slows down the game too much. As with my heavily-modded Minecraft install, or similar KSP, I'm saddened to reach the point where my base simply slows the game down too much to be playable.- physics simulation: due to simulation issues (and gameplay constraints born out of using Newtonian physics*) the maximum speed of any object (except fired bullets, lasers) is set at around 110 m/s; this is relative to an implicit fixed point. While the game had asteroids, this was less glaring; with the introduction of planets, this became much more of a problem. The planets are tiny - to make them reachable and orbitable - tens of km (or tens of miles, doesn't make much difference) in diameter; atmospheric entries at 110m/s are as hot as day-old soup and entirely unexciting.- optimisation, bugs: relatively poorly optimised (but, hey, at least it's not written in Java) and with a lot of programming bugs and gameplay kinks. While this is normal for an alpha game, I still have to evaluate the game for what it is.- poor interface: the interface was designed for a less-complex game (or this game a few years ago). Large, clunky, and requiring many clicks and keypresses to get where desired, it needs a serious overhaul.Conclusion:While less suited to building cities of the stars, and more suited to mid-size projects or conflict-eroded multiplayer faction bases, the game does play its strengths well.Ultimately, I've had a fun experience with Space Engineers; the fact that I've spent the time to build my bases up to a grinding halt tells that I've been sucked into the game, constantly planning and building, and enjoying myself.-----------------Physics & gameplay rant below:* The issue of speed in Newtonian Mechanics vs. gameplay constraints has been discussed in the past. For instance, a few years back EVE Online(well, CCP) argued for speed limits (and against Newtonian Mechanics) since, given two ships of the same class, the follower would never be able to catch up to the followed.Still, I feel that a free-build game has many options open for it to remove the low - and sudden - speed limit.General Relativity max-speed (exponentially difficult to approach, never achieve) provides a good dimishing-returns curve. Bell's Two-ship problem - meaning that, in General Relativity, an identical follower would never be able to catch up to the followed - can be circumvented by stripping down ships to the bare minimum (or adding more engines); higher-acceleration interception ships can catch up to slower ones, while being poor at frontline combat due to the high ratio of engines to ship mass (i.e. trade-offs, ship designed for roles and around constraints, emergent gameplay, fun!).Also, a ship travelling very fast can still be shot down with lasers (due to frame of reference interactions, the laser catching up to the fast ship moves still at the speed of light, from the point of view of, well, everybody in the universe), though aiming might be more of a challenge. Add to this emergent game constraints, like energy, life support, front gammaray shielding, interstellar hydrogen impacts and so on, and I conclude that, while difficult, a very large speed limit is feasible to implement and possibly fun to play with."
