76561198057142927,Recommended,244850,33321871,Posted: 6 July,all,ElectroVeeDub,"Haters gonna hate...If you take a quick look through all the reviews here, you'll notice that there's some mixed reviews with people complaining about bugs in Space Engineers. They're just being whiny little kids.Of course there's bugs. The game is still in Beta development. Games that have the countless hours of fun that we all want take literally years to develop. It's not an instantaneous endeavour. Keen Software House has done a fine job of updating their games on a WEEKLY basis, with videos uploaded to YouTube highlighting their patches and new content. Keen does it's best to keep it's playerbase informed, and in my opinion does a much better job at it than most other developers I've ever seen. No bull... weekly updates.Space Engineers is a game where your imagination, and gaming rig, are the only limits. Wanna build a Star Destroyer from Star Wars then insta-pwn other players in PVP fashion? No problem. Wanna kick back with a beer and play solo, and build the international space station? Do it. Wanna invent ridiculous super weapons strapped to 1000m long ships that hurl a thousand asteroids at a base at 18,000 kmph smashing it into oblivion? Completely possible. Wanna start off a map where you have 15 minutes to find oxygen and build necessities, or you're dead? Welcome to Space Engineers.Regardless of what others say, this game is more than worth the asking price. I'd have no problem paying $60 for it. I'm happy I've supported the developers, and I have no regrets about the purchase. I do find the planets to be buggy compared to the outer-space maps however. The spider-like mobs tend to clip through blocks. They have terrible AI. Theres texture pop-up. Odd rock formations floating mid air. And other general irregularities. No doubt it'll get fixed one day.Space Engineers offers you a multiplayer paradise that is the obvious graduation from other sandbox games like MineCraft. If you've played others, and are looking for a deeper expierience with more crafting, resource gathering, pvp, pve, and teamwork... look no further. You can host your own servers, join other servers, or just decide to play solo. There's ruthless PVP where people try to kill you and destroy everything you built... and there's servers where its peacfull and people cooperate towards a common goal. Whatever you like.. you'll find it. Just be prepared... it's a very complicated game with a bit of a steep learning curve. I wouldn't recommend it for kids or people with no patience. There's tons of menus and options. Physics, inertia, and science is a major part of everything you'll do in this game.The community is unusually helpful and well behaved. Need a friend to play with? Live in a US/Canadian timezone with a microphone? Send me a friend request. I know people who can get you trained up. Do you have a silly question? Post a thread on the forums: nobody will laugh at you.There's a mind boggling amount of mods and community created content that are downloadable from Steam. Want a blue-print to build the USS Enterprise NC-1701D? But you don't have 60 hours to engineer the ship yourself? No problem. It's on the workshop no doubt.So if you're a sandbox fan with a genuine amount of ""Geek in space building stuff"" in your blood... give Space Engineers a shot.I'm impressed. It's a great game with huge potential."
